sec.p:
Axiidean ghost shrimps are lobster-like decapod crustaceans (
Dworschak et al . 2012
) inhabiting the intertidal to deep-sea soft-bottom substrates ( Dworschak 2000 ), and their bioturbating activities are known to cause long-term effects on the geophysical and geochemical characters of the bottom sediments ( Rowden & Jones 1993 ;
Ziebis et al . 1996
;
Rowden et al . 1998 a , 1998b) and benthic community patterns ( Tamaki 1994 ; Wynberg & Branch 1994 ). Despite their ecological significance, documentation of their occurrence in the Indian waters is inadequate.

The Indian axiidean fauna is represented by 18 species of 16 genera in 4 families known from all coasts from intertidal to slope depths (
Table 1
). It is shortly noted at present that the following 7 species were erroneously listed as the Indian species by 
Sakai (2011)
; 
Corallianassa borradailei
(de 
Man, 1928
)

(
Maldives
), 
C. longiventris
(A. 
Milne-Edwards, 1870
) (
Maldives
, 
Pakistan
, 
Sri Lanka
); 
C. martensi
(
Miers, 1884
)

(
Pakistan
, 
Sri Lanka
), 
Glypturus armatus
(A. 
Milne-Edwards, 1870
) (
Indonesia
); 
Neocallichirus manningi
Kazmi QB & Kazmi MA, 1992

(
Pakistan
), 
N. mauritianus
(
Miers, 1882
)

(
Mauritius
), and 
Paratrypaea bouvieri
(
Nobili, 1904
)

(
Sri Lanka
).

